file-name: XC146359-pipit des arbres cris sisisisi 7 et 8 p33 nid du corb 210406 14h44.mp3
rmk: This is a rare call I have just recorded two or three times in 9 years . Always uttered from the ground, it's constitued by a serie of ascending and then descending notes. And beteween those notes, the bird utters the traditionnal "si" territorial call. Always uttered at the begining of the breeding season, perhaps during the nest construction, it could be a kind of copulating incitement. See also XC146356.

rmk: Flight calls given during autumn migration. The 3rd and 4th call very much resemble water/rock pipit. After analysis of both calls and comparing with criteria published bij Fijen (Dutch Birding, 2014, 36 (2):87-95) and discussion with the author, the calls fit neither of the two species (incl ssp. *spinoletta*) very well, although it is closer to water than rock pipit based on the criteria. The recording data (Aug 31) is however too early in autumn for a Water Pipit to migrate over NL. Looking at the rhythm at which all calls are given, all recorded calls are presumably given by the same bird, i.e. a Tree Pipit.
